-- в”Ђв”Ђ Rygel в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$A free, open-source UPnP AV MediaServer and MediaRenderer for the GNOME desktop that shares audio, video, and photos across a home network and streams to DLNA and UPnP devices.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open source, no commercial pricing$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2008, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Rygel Guide 2026: GNOME UPnP and DLNA Media Server$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$What Rygel is, how the open-source GNOME UPnP and DLNA media server works, and its key features for sharing media across a home network.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Rygel is a free, open-source home media solution developed as part of the GNOME desktop ecosystem, implementing both a UPnP AV MediaServer and a MediaRenderer through a plug-in architecture. Development work on Rygel traces back to its first commit in April 2008, making it one of the longer-running components in the GNOME project family, and it is licensed under LGPL-2.1-or-later, with accompanying documentation under CC-BY-SA-3.0. Rygel is written largely in the Vala programming language and is built on top of GUPnP, GNOME's UPnP implementation library. Because it is a community-maintained open-source project under the GNOME umbrella rather than a commercial company, Rygel has no pricing, no company headquarters, and no disclosed employee count; it is maintained by volunteer and GNOME-affiliated contributors and distributed through Linux package repositories such as Fedora and via the GNOME GitLab instance. Functionally, Rygel lets a user share audio, video, and photo libraries stored on a Linux PC with other devices on the same home network, including smart TVs, games consoles such as the Sony PlayStation and Microsoft Xbox, DLNA-compatible speakers, and smartphones, without those files needing to be manually copied to each device. As a MediaRenderer, Rygel can also receive and play media pushed to it from another controller device, effectively turning a Linux machine into a networked playback target. One of Rygel's most useful capabilities is automatic transcoding: when a client device cannot natively play the format of the original media file, Rygel can transcode it on the fly into a compatible format so playback still works without the user needing to convert files manually in advance. The project ships a main server binary along with a set of plugins and shared libraries that other developers can use to build their own Rygel plugins, custom media engines, standalone renderers, or entirely separate UPnP and DLNA server implementations, reflecting its role as both an end-user application and a reusable library layer within the GNOME stack. Rygel is aimed at Linux desktop users, particularly those running GNOME, who want to stream personal media libraries to televisions, consoles, and other DLNA or UPnP-certified hardware on a local network without relying on proprietary or cloud-based media server software.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '1269899d-d0a4-4fea-afe2-1530e36e1f6f';

