-- в”Ђв”Ђ Safebucket в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$An open-source, self-hosted file sharing platform where files upload and download directly to your own S3-compatible storage rather than passing through the application server.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open source, self-hosted$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Safebucket Review 2026: Open-Source Self-Hosted File Sharing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$What Safebucket is, how its direct-to-storage architecture works, and its key features for open-source, self-hosted secure file sharing.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Safebucket is an open-source, self-hosted file sharing platform built around the principle that uploaded and downloaded files never pass through the application's own server. Instead, clients connect directly to a storage backend using presigned URLs, so Safebucket's server only handles metadata, access control, and audit logging rather than proxying file bytes. The project is licensed under the Apache 2.0 license and is built with a Go backend REST API and a React with TypeScript frontend, giving it a modern, developer-friendly technology stack. Because Safebucket is a community open-source project distributed through GitHub rather than a registered company with disclosed funding or headcount, there is no publicly documented founding year, company size, or headquarters; it is designed to be deployed by the organizations that use it rather than operated as a hosted SaaS product by its creators. Architecturally, every major component of Safebucket is swappable: storage can be backed by AWS S3, Google Cloud Storage, MinIO, Wasabi, Backblaze B2, DigitalOcean Spaces, Linode Object Storage, Tencent COS, Alibaba OSS, or any other S3-compatible provider; the database can be PostgreSQL or SQLite; events can flow through NATS JetStream, AWS SQS, or GCP Pub/Sub; caching can use Redis, Valkey, or an in-memory store; and activity logs can be sent to Loki or the local filesystem. Authentication is SSO-first, connecting to an organization's existing identity provider via OIDC so Safebucket does not need to manage user passwords itself. Sharing is organized around buckets with explicit membership and role-based permissions, distinguishing owners, contributors, and viewers, and the platform includes quick and reverse share links for sending files externally with configurable protections such as a password, a maximum number of downloads, and a maximum number of views. Additional features include real-time activity tracking and audit logs for compliance visibility, multifactor authentication via TOTP, and file expiration with configurable trash retention periods so deleted files are not immediately unrecoverable. Safebucket supports several deployment paths, including a stated one-minute local lite setup for quick evaluation, as well as production deployment on AWS and other cloud environments. The platform is aimed at organizations that already have their own identity provider and object storage infrastructure and want a lightweight, auditable file sharing layer on top of it, rather than businesses looking for a fully managed, vendor-hosted file sharing SaaS product.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '991a14b4-c72d-4cf5-87f7-81f3fc26205a';

